window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2005>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2005","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"SIMPLE HARMONIC MOTION : PERIOD, FREQUENCY AND AMPLITUDE OF A BODY EXECUTING S.H.M","question":"You have been provided with a retort stand, clamp and boss, a set of masses, a spiral spring, stop watch, split cork and other necessary apparatus.    Use the diagram beside as a guide, carry out the following instructions:     (i) Suspend the spiral spring vertically as shown in the diagram  (ii) Suspend the mass hanger on the free end of the spiral spring and add mass, m = 50.0 g to the hanger  (iii) Pull the hanger gently downwards and release to set it into vertical oscillations.  (iv) Determine the time, t, for 20 complete oscillations   (v) Evaluate the period, T, of the oscillations. Also evaluate T2  (vi) Repeat the procedure for four other values of m = 70, 90, 110, and 130 g. In each case, determine t and evaluate T and T2. Tabulate your readings.  (vii) Plot a graph of  T2 on the vertical axis against m on the horizontal axis.  (viii) Determine the slope, s, of the graph and the intercept I, on the vertical axis.  (ix) Evaluate k = 4\u03c02s\\frac{4\u03c0^{2}}{s}s4\u03c02\u200b (Take \u03c0= 227\\frac{22}{7}722\u200b)  (x) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"No of oscillations = 20    S/Nm(g)       t1(s)       t2(s)      T=t1+t22\\frac{t_{1}+t_{2}}{2}2t1\u200b+t2\u200b\u200b(s)        T(s)      T2(s2)1506.806.806.806.8046.242707.607.607.607.6057.763908.408.408.408.4070.5641108.808.808.808.8077.44513010.0010.0010.0010.00100.00          (viii) s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 95\u221247.5130\u221250\\frac{95-47.5}{130-50}130\u22125095\u221247.5\u200b = 1932\\frac{19}{32}3219\u200b = 0.59    I = 12.5    (ix) k = 4\u03c02s\\frac{4\u03c0^{2}}{s}s4\u03c02\u200b = 4\u00d7(227)20.59\\frac{4\u00d7\\left(\\frac{22}{7}\\right)^{2}}{0.59}0.594\u00d7(722\u200b)2\u200b = 66.97    (x)  Precautions:   1. I carefully checked and corrected for any zero error on the timing device before recording the period of oscillation to ensure accurate measurements.  2. I took multiple readings of the period and calculated the average to minimize the effects of random errors and improve the reliability of the results.  3. I used a stable setup to prevent external disturbances from affecting the oscillations and introducing variability in the measurements.  4. I made sure the oscillating object returned to the same starting point for each cycle to maintain consistency in timing.  5. I avoided any parallax error by positioning my eye directly in line with the stop watch when taking readings.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2005>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2005","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"HOOKE\u2019S LAW, YOUNG\u2019S MODULES AND WORK DONE IN SPRINGS AND STRING :","question":"Define Young modulus and force constant.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Young's Modulus:  Young's modulus is a measure of the stiffness of a material. It is defined as the ratio of stress (force per unit area) to strain (relative deformation) within the elastic limit of the material. Mathematically,  Young's Modulus (Y) = StressStrain\\frac{Stress}{Strain}StrainStress\u200b = FA\u0394LL0\\frac{\\frac{F}{A}}{\\frac{\u0394L}{L_{0}}}L0\u200b\u0394L\u200bAF\u200b\u200b  where F is the applied force, A is the cross-sectional area, \u0394L is the change in length, and L0\u200b is the original length. A higher Young's modulus indicates a stiffer material.  Force Constant:  The force constant, also known as the spring constant, is a measure of a spring's stiffness. It defines the amount of force required to produce a unit extension or compression in a spring. According to Hooke's law, it is given by:  k = Fe\\frac{F}{e}eF\u200b  where k is the force constant, F is the applied force, and e is the displacement from equilibrium. A higher force constant means the spring is stiffer and requires more force to stretch or compress.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2005>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2005","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"HOOKE\u2019S LAW, YOUNG\u2019S MODULES AND WORK DONE IN SPRINGS AND STRING :","question":"A force of magnitude 500 N is applied to the free end of a spiral spring of force constant 1.0 \u00d7 104 Nm-1. Calculate the energy stored in the spring.    (Please provide your answer with the unit e.g 123.123 N)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"W = 12\\frac{1}{2}21\u200bFe = 12\\frac{1}{2}21\u200bF \u00d7 Fk\\frac{F}{k}kF\u200b = F22k\\frac{F^{2}}{2k}2kF2\u200b = 50022\u00d7104\\frac{500^{2}}{2\u00d710^{4}}2\u00d71045002\u200b = 12.5 J","marks":"1","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2005>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2005","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"Using the diagram above as a guide;    (i) Trace the outline ABC of the equilateral triangular glass prism provided.  (ii) Remove the prism. Draw the line MN such that it makes an angle i = 5\u00b0 with the normal at  N  on the side AB of the outline  (iii) Fix two pins at P1 and P2 on MN. Replace the prism on its outline.   (iv) Looking through the face BC of the prism, fix one pin at P3 and the other at P4 such that they are in a straight line with the images of the pins P1 and P2  (v) Remove the prisms and the pins. Draw a line to join P4 and P3. Produce the line P4 P3 to meet the line BC of the outline at Q and line MN produced at P.  (vi) Draw the normal to BC at Q. Measure and record the angles \u03b8 and e. Evaluate \u2205 = i + e  (vii) Repeat the procedure using different outline in each case, for the four other values of i = 10\u00b0, 15\u00b0, 20\u00b0 and 25\u00b0 respectively. Evaluate \u2205 = i + e. Tabulate your readings.  (viii) Plot a graph of \u03b8 on the vertical against \u2205 on he horizontal axis starting both axes from the origin (0,0).   (ix) Determine the slope of the graph and the intercept on the vertical axis.  (x) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/Ni\u00b0e\u00b0\u03b8\u00b0\u2205 = i + e \u00b015.05.050.010.0210.09.040.019.0315.015.030.120.0420.019.020.039.0525.023.011.048.0        (ix) slope = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 47\u22121310\u221245\\frac{47-13}{10-45}10\u22124547\u221213\u200b = -3435\\frac{34}{35}3534\u200b = -0.97    intercept = 56      (xi)  Precautions:     1. I ensured that both the object and image pins were perfectly straight and perpendicular to the surface to prevent parallax error and obtain accurate alignment when taking readings.  2. I firmly secured the pins into the surface to keep them fully upright, ensuring they remained stable and erect during measurement to avoid misalignment.  3. I positioned my eye level directly in line with the pins when aligning them to minimize any parallax error that could affect accuracy.  4. I double-checked the alignment of the pins before each reading to maintain consistent positioning and reduce errors due to accidental movement.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2005>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2005","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"Explain what is meant by the statement the refractive index of glass is 1.65.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The statement \"the refractive index of a material is 1.65\" means that light travels 1.65 times slower in that material compared to how it travels in a vacuum. In other words, the ratio of the speed of light in a vacuum to the speed of light in the material is 1.65. The refractive index (n) quantifies how much the light ray bends when it enters the material from another medium, such as air. A higher refractive index indicates a greater reduction in the speed of light and more bending.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2005>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2005","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"LIGHT WAVES : REFRACTION OF LIGHT AT PLANE SURFACES","question":"Calculate the critical angle of  medium of refractive index 1.65 when light passes fro the medium to air.    (Please provide your answer to 2 d.p and without the unit)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"sin C = 1n\\frac{1}{n}n1\u200b = 11.65\\frac{1}{1.65}1.651\u200b = 0.6061    C = sin-1(0.6061)    \u2234 C = 37.31\u00b0","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2005>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2005","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"You are provided with a potentiometer XY, voltmeter, V, a standard resistor R, an accumulator, e, a plug key, K, a jockey and connecting wires.    (i) Connect the circuit as shown in the diagram above  (ii) Close the key and use the jockey to make contact with the potentiometer wire XY at a point  N  such that  l  = XN =15cm.  (iii) Read and record the value of the potential difference V on the voltmeter.  (iv) Evaluate  l -1 and V-1  (v) Repeat the procedure for five other value of  l  = 25, 35, 45, 55, and 65 cm respectively. Read and record the values of V and V-1 and  l  -1 in each case. Tabulate your readings  (vi) Plot a graph of V-1 on the vertical axis  against  l  -1 on the horizontal axis, starting both axes from the origin (0,0)   (vii) Determine the slope, s, of the graph  (viii) Evaluate k = 1s\\frac{1}{s}s1\u200b  (ix) State two precautions, taken to ensure accurate results","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"S/N l (cm) l -1(cm-1)V(V)V-1(V-1)115.000.06660.07513.33225.000.04000.08511.76335.000.02860.09510.53445.000.02220.1059.52555.000.01820.1158.69665.000.01540.1258.00        (vii) s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 13\u221290.0575\u22120.0175\\frac{13-9}{0.0575-0.0175}0.0575\u22120.017513\u22129\u200b = 100    (viii) k = 1s\\frac{1}{s}s1\u200b = 1100\\frac{1}{100}1001\u200b = 0.01    (ix)  Precautions:   1. I carefully placed the jockey on the potentiometer wire without scraping or pressing too hard to prevent damaging the wire and maintain uniform resistance across its length.  2. I kept the circuit key open when the circuit was not in use to conserve the cells and prevent unnecessary battery drain, ensuring consistent power for measurements.  3. I avoided any sharp or forceful movements of the jockey along the potentiometer wire to prevent localized wear and maintain the accuracy of the wire's resistance.  4. I inspected all connections to ensure they were secure, preventing any loose contacts that could affect current flow and measurement reliability.  5. I minimized physical contact with the potentiometer wire and other conductive parts to avoid interference from body heat or oils, which could alter the resistance.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2005>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2005","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : RESISTIVITY AND CONDUCTIVITY","question":"State four factors on which the resistance of a wire depend.","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The resistance of a wire depends on the following four factors:    1. Length of the Wire  2. Cross-sectional Area  3. Material of the Wire  4. Temperature    1. Length of the Wire: Resistance increases with the length of the wire; a longer wire has higher resistance.  2. Cross-sectional Area: Resistance decreases as the cross-sectional area increases; a thicker wire has lower resistance.  3. Material of the Wire: Different materials have different resistivities; for example, copper has lower resistance compared to iron for the same length and thickness.  4. Temperature: Resistance generally increases with temperature, as higher temperatures cause more atomic vibrations, which impede the flow of electrons.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2005>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2005","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC ENERGY AND POWER","question":"A resistance wire of length 100 cm is connected in a circuit. if the resistance per unit length of the wire is 0.02 \u03a9cm-1, how much heat would be produced in the wire if a voltmeter connected across its ends indicate 1.5 V while the current runs for 1 minute?    (Provide your answer with the unit e.g 123.123 N)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"V = IR    R = 0.02 \u03a9cm-1 \u00d7 100 cm = 2 \u03a9    t = 1 min = 60 s    H = I2Rt = (VR)2\\left(\\frac{V}{R}\\right)^{2}(RV\u200b)2 \u00d7 R \u00d7 t = V2tR\\frac{V^{2}t}{R}RV2t\u200b = 1.52\u00d7602\\frac{1.5^{2}\u00d760}{2}21.52\u00d760\u200b = 67.5 J","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"}];